\ sort ( arr -- arr ): a NEW array ordered by the system total order (val_cmp) —
\ the same order =, lt, and sets use. Duplicates are kept; the source is unchanged.

\ floats: ascending, duplicates kept, negatives and non-integers
[ 3 1 2 1 3 ] sort . cr             \ [ 1 1 2 3 3 ]
[ 5 4 3 2 1 ] sort . cr             \ reverse input -> ascending
[ -2 0 -5 3.5 1.5 -5 ] sort . cr    \ negatives and fractions ordered, -5 twice
[ 42 ] sort . cr                    \ single element
[ ] sort . cr                       \ empty

\ already sorted is a fixed point
[ 1 2 3 ] sort . cr

\ idempotent: sorting twice equals sorting once
[ 3 1 2 ] sort sort  [ 3 1 2 ] sort  = . cr   \ 1

\ functional: the source array is not mutated
[ 9 7 8 ] dup sort drop . cr        \ [ 9 7 8 ]

\ strings: lexicographic; a prefix sorts before its extension; duplicates kept
[ "pear" "apple" "ab" "a" "apple" ] sort . cr

\ mixed tags group in tag order (float < string), ordered within each tag
[ "z" 3 1 "a" 2 ] sort . cr         \ [ 1 2 3 "a" "z" ]

\ nested arrays compared element-wise (val_cmp recurses; shorter prefix first)
[ [ 2 ] [ 1 ] [ 1 0 ] [ 1 ] ] sort . cr   \ [ [ 1 ] [ 1 ] [ 1 0 ] [ 2 ] ]

\ symbols order by interning order, not alphabetically (val_cmp compares the
\ interned offset) — included to document that, not as alphabetical sorting
[ :gamma :alpha :beta ] sort . cr

\ only arrays sort
5 sort . cr                         \ error: not an array
< 3 1 2 > sort . cr                 \ error: a set is not an array
